<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-17</title>

<p>This run scouts the July 16 Hugging Face daily pool (24 papers; the July 17 page had not gone live at scout time). No flagship model dropped, but three papers reward a deep look, and they rhyme in a way that feels like the moment we're in: each rebuilds a piece of the ML stack so that <b>agents can operate it directly</b>. A robot world-action model whose future-prediction stream is structurally optional at test time shipped with open code <i>and</i> weights; a "handbook" makes production agent harnesses navigable and editable by the coding agents that must maintain them; and a simulator turns all of Unreal Engine into a Python-callable surface by hooking the engine's reflection system rather than wrapping it. Each thread below was verified against code, checkpoint headers, or a working probe — not just the PDF.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> GigaWorld-Policy-0.5 (arXiv 2607.13960) is the first world-action-model release to arrive with full code and a 6B checkpoint one day after the paper. The "train with future video, infer action-only" recipe is now reproducible and inspectable, and its causal-mask mechanism survives bit-level verification. Honest caveat: architecturally it is convergent evolution on FastWAM, executed well.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 1: World-Action Models, Priced for the Edge</h1>

<p>World Action Models couple action generation with future-video prediction so that imagined scene evolution supervises the policy densely. The catch: most WAMs pay for that supervision twice — once in training, and again at deployment, where every control step literally renders the imagined future (Motus clocks 3,231 ms per chunk on an A100). This thread asks how the future stream can be made <i>exactly</i> optional at inference, and whether the published latency and success claims hold up when you read the released code and checkpoint.</p>

<h2>GigaWorld-Policy-0.5: A Faster and Stronger WAM Empowered by AutoResearch</h2>
<p>GigaWorld Team et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.13960">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.13960">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/open-gigaai/giga-world-policy">code</a> · <a href="https://huggingface.co/open-gigaai/Giga-World-Policy-0.5">weights</a> · <a href="https://open-gigaai.github.io/giga-world-policy/">project</a></p>

<p>The release is the story before the method is: GigaAI shipped the training/inference repo and a 24 GB fp32 checkpoint (transformer only, on top of a Wan2.2-TI2V-5B VAE/T5 stack) the day after the arXiv posting. That turned this thread from a read-and-summarize into a code-and-weights verification — the mask was reconstructed in numpy, parameter counts were pulled from the checkpoint's safetensors headers via HTTP range requests, and a FLOP model was built to check the latency claims.</p>

<p><b>The mechanism: a four-block causal mask that makes the future an information sink.</b> The token sequence is laid out as <code>[state | action | ref | future]</code>, where state+action form the action stream and ref (current frames)+future form the visual stream. The attention allow-matrix in <code>build_mot_attention_mask()</code> is:</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="150"/><col width="90"/><col width="90"/><col width="90"/><col width="90"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">query \ key</th><th background-color="light-gray">state</th><th background-color="light-gray">action</th><th background-color="light-gray">ref</th><th background-color="light-gray">future</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><b>state</b></td><td>✓</td><td>✗</td><td>✓</td><td>✗</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>action</b></td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td><td><b>✗</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>ref</b></td><td>✓</td><td>✗</td><td>✓</td><td>✗</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>future</b></td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Read the action row carefully: action tokens never attend to future tokens, so no future information can leak into the policy. Read the future row: future tokens attend to <i>everything, including all 48 action tokens</i> — so the future-prediction loss is literally an action-conditioned world-modeling loss, and it backprops into the action representations. The future stream is a pure information sink: it reads the policy's tokens, and nothing reads it. A numpy reimplementation of the mask proves the consequence exactly: deleting the entire future block leaves every other token's attention output bit-identical (max diff ~2e-16). That is why "future prediction is optional at inference" is an exact structural fact here, not an approximation — and a counterfactual probe shows that if action→future attention leaked, dropping the future stream would shift action outputs by up to 0.26.</p>

<p><b>The Mixture-of-Transformers split, validated to the byte.</b> Inside each MoT block, self-attention is joint — each expert computes its own Q/K/V, the projections are concatenated across streams, and one masked attention runs over both. Everything else is per-expert: output projections, cross-attention to the umT5 text embedding, FFN, and adaLN tables. From the released checkpoint headers: 6.0216 B parameters total = visual expert 4.91 B (81.5%) + action expert 1.01 B (16.7%) + ~103 M embeddings, an exact match with the HF metadata. One subtle implementation detail: the action expert's attention still projects to the same 3,072-dim inner space as the visual expert (24 heads × 128) so that K/V can concatenate; it is lightweight via its width (1,024) and FFN (4,096 vs 14,336), not via head geometry. During action-only inference the per-step active parameters are just the 1.0 B action expert — the visual expert runs once per chunk on the ~121-token prefix and its K/V is cached. The full training sequence is only 289 tokens: 120 ref + 120 future + 48 action + 1 state (the Wan2.2 VAE's 16× spatial / 4× temporal compression collapses four future RGB frames into a single latent frame).</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:gigaworld-policy-05:mot-architecture]]</p>

<p><b>Does the latency story add up? Mostly, with one fairness flag.</b> A per-chunk FLOP model built from the traced config (10 flow-matching steps, no classifier-free guidance) reproduces the paper's ratios well: action-only inference costs 2.18 TFLOP/chunk; the dense v1 architecture would cost 5.93 TFLOP (2.72× model prediction vs. 2.66× measured on a 4090, 293→110 ms); running the full joint WAM with future generation would cost ~24.9 TFLOP, an 11.4× multiple consistent with Motus's 3,231 ms. The paper's Table 4 with the probe's compute column:</p>

