  <colgroup><col width="170"/><col width="95"/><col width="95"/><col width="100"/><col width="120"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Method</th><th background-color="light-gray">A100 (ms) ↓</th><th background-color="light-gray">4090 (ms) ↓</th><th background-color="light-gray">Real-robot SR ↑</th><th background-color="light-gray">TFLOP/chunk (probe)</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>π0.5</td><td>225</td><td>110</td><td>0.76</td><td>—</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Motus</td><td>3,231</td><td>—</td><td>0.80</td><td>~25 class (joint)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>FastWAM</td><td>229</td><td>182</td><td>0.78</td><td>—</td></tr>
    <tr><td>GigaWorld-Policy (v1)</td><td>360</td><td>293</td><td>0.80</td><td>5.93 (dense)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>GigaWorld-Policy-0.5</b></td><td><b>189</b></td><td><b>110</b></td><td><b>0.85</b></td><td><b>2.18</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td>GigaWorld-Policy-0.5 + C++</td><td>140</td><td><b>85</b></td><td>0.85</td><td>2.18</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Three caveats before quoting the 85 ms headline. First, the C++ row compares GigaWorld's <b>C++ runtime against Python numbers for every baseline</b> — there are no C++ baseline counterparts, and the C++ runtime itself is <i>not in the released repo</i> (only a Python server/client ships). Second, π0.5's measurement conditions are unstated, and FastWAM's own paper reports 190 ms on its own setup, so cross-paper latency is not apples-to-apples. Third, the success-rate deltas (0.85 vs 0.80 for the strongest baselines) sit well inside 10-trial noise. The honest summary: the 2.7× architectural speedup over v1 is real and compute-verified; the "23%/53% faster than π0.5/FastWAM" framing leans on an unshipped runtime.</p>

<p><b>AutoResearch: an agent wrote the recipe — genuinely, but shallowly.</b> The citation <code>[karpathy2026autoresearch]</code> is Karpathy's March-2026 <code>autoresearch</code> loop (~66 k GitHub stars): a coding agent edits a training script, runs bounded pilot experiments, keeps changes that improve the metric, discards the rest. GigaWorld applies it to post-training configuration on pick-the-fruit (930 episodes, 300 train / 30 val): 1K-step pilot sweeps, then promotion to longer runs. Figure 7 shows real loop semantics rather than a relabeled grid search — a gray "observe" bar at lr 4.3e-5 (this resolves Table 5's otherwise bizarre 4.316e-5: it's the <i>inherited baseline</i>, not an agent-invented value), agent-proposed candidates at 3/6/8e-5, batch-size probes at 12 and 8, a frames=64 run abandoned early, and an extension phase where the 30K-step checkpoint is kept and the 50K one is discarded as a regression. The agent's actual finding is a real multi-objective call: lr 6e-5 gives the best action MSE (0.4098) while 3e-5 gives the best <i>visual</i> loss (0.1723) — and since action quality is what executes, 6e-5 wins. The shipped finetune config is exactly the agent's output: lr 6e-5, batch 16, constant schedule. The honest read: this is disciplined pilot sweeping with keep/discard semantics — a handful of single-factor probes around a strong baseline, no code or architecture mutations, and the multi-objective conflict resolved by a hard-coded action-over-visual preference rather than Pareto reasoning. Useful, shippable, and much closer to "agent as lab assistant" than to autonomous research. One unresolved discrepancy to flag: pilot-phase eval action MSE (~0.41) and long-run values (~1e-4) differ by ~4,000×; the paper never explains the rescaling.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:gigaworld-policy-05:autoresearch]]</p>

<p><b>Novelty, honestly.</b> "Train with future video, infer action-only" is not new — FastWAM (arXiv 2603.16666) already combined an MoT with shared attention, a structured mask, and no future generation at test time, and GigaWorld-Policy v1 already had the action-centered mask. What is genuinely new here: (1) future tokens attend to <i>action</i> tokens inside the joint network — FastWAM's video branch is not action-conditioned (its future attends only to a first-frame anchor and itself) — plus a mixed AC-WM+WAM pretraining stage that doubles down on action↔dynamics coupling; (2) a validated lightweight action expert (1.0 B active of 6.0 B total) whose compute advantage checks out end-to-end; (3) deployment engineering (prefix KV cache, torch.compile, C++ runtime claim) with reproducible Python-side numbers; (4) a recipe produced by an agent loop, warts and all. FastWAM's own ablation strengthens the shared thesis: removing video co-training collapses its real-world towel-folding success to 10% — the training-time video objective, not test-time imagination, carries the value. Errata worth knowing: Figure 6's AC-WM ablation legend appears swapped (the "w/o AC-WM" curve reaches 0.85, contradicting the caption — the text's claim matches the swapped reading); the repo config and inference script use action_dim=32 while the checkpoint is strictly 16-channel, so loading breaks unless you align them; and the arXiv v1 bibliography is broken (all citations render as keys).</p>

<h1>Theme 2: The Agent-Maintained Stack</h1>

<p>As coding agents take over the evolution of software systems, the bottleneck shifts from writing edits to <b>finding where a behavior lives</b>. This theme's deep thread attacks that localization problem head-on; the noticed papers around it cover the rest of the operational loop — attributing agent failures, compressing traces for optimization, self-evolving skills, and injecting compiler feedback into generation itself.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="200"/><col width="230"/><col width="230"/><col width="90"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Paper</th><th background-color="light-gray">Key Contribution</th><th background-color="light-gray">Why It Matters</th><th background-color="light-gray">Links</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><b>Self-Improvements in Modern Agentic Systems: A Survey</b> (2026)</td><td>Frames self-improving agents as adaptive systems converting experience into capability gains; agent = model + operational scaffold (prompts, memory, tools, control logic).</td><td>A current map of the design space that the Harness Handbook and the GUIClaw self-evolution loop live in.</td><td><a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.13104">HF</a> / <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.13104">PDF</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Tracing Agentic Failure from the Flow of Success</b> (2026)</td><td>Unsupervised failure attribution: trains on success trajectories only, flags which steps in a failed trajectory caused the failure — no step-level error annotations.</td><td>Cheap failure localization is the missing companion to expensive LLM-judge debugging pipelines.</td><td><a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.12747">HF</a> / <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.12747">PDF</a></td></tr>
