<h2>Harness Handbook: Making Evolving Agent Harnesses Readable, Navigable, and Editable</h2>
<p>Wang, Shi et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.13285">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.13285">PDF</a> · <a href="https://ruhan-wang.github.io/Harness-Handbook/">project</a></p>

<p>The paper's premise will be obvious to anyone who has asked a coding agent to change a non-trivial behavior in a large repo: the request describes <i>what the system should do</i>, but the repository is organized by files, functions, and modules — and a single behavior (say, "require three completion confirmations before grading") is usually smeared across an initialization site, a reset site, and two branches of a loop. The authors name this prerequisite of every modification <b>behavior localization</b>, and argue it — not edit generation — is the central bottleneck in harness evolution.</p>

<p>The answer is a behavior-centric artifact: an L1–L3 document tree (system overview → per-stage component overviews → source-backed unit cards) plus a cross-stage <b>state-register view</b> that records, for every piece of shared state, every location that reads or writes it. Two invariants keep it honest: progressive disclosure (descend only when needed) and behavior–implementation alignment (every L3 source locator is revalidated against the live repository; locators that fail are <i>frozen, never guessed</i>). Construction is three-phase: deterministic static analysis extracts a program graph (unresolved calls go to an audit log — again, never guessed), an LLM proposer–reviewer loop organizes functions or files into execution stages, and synthesis builds the tree with validated locators. After every non-empty diff, a resync pass updates only the affected entries, matching functions by body fingerprints that ignore line numbers. A nice meta-detail: the handbook is exposed to the planning agent as a <code>SKILL.md</code> manifest — literally an agent skill, with navigation instructions, that points to overview/index/register/stage reference files.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:harness-handbook:structure]]</p>

<p><b>The probe: build a tiny one on the real Terminus-2.</b> The paper releases no code, no constructed handbooks, and none of its 60 modification requests — but the Terminus-2 harness it evaluates on is public inside the Harbor framework (5 Python files, 3,914 LOC; the paper says 6 files / 103 functions — snapshot drift). So this run rebuilt the pipeline in miniature with stdlib <code>ast</code>: parse the repo, resolve the call graph (107 functions, 195 resolved edges vs. the paper's 257 — the missing quarter hides in aliases, callbacks, inheritance, and <code>getattr</code>/<code>@retry</code> dynamic dispatch; 318 unresolved calls correctly logged, not guessed), detect 68 <code>self._*</code> state registers, and emit an overview/index/registers/stages handbook. Then the behavior-localization demo from the paper's own Appendix E ("require three consecutive task_complete marks") was run against it:</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="210"/><col width="240"/><col width="240"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Approach</th><th background-color="light-gray">Sites surfaced</th><th background-color="light-gray">Verdict</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><code>grep -rn task_complete</code></td><td>41 hits across 5 files (prompt templates ×9, both parsers ×20, loop ×12)</td><td>Mirrored implementations and doc strings — real noise even in a 4 kLOC repo</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Handbook register view (<code>_pending_completion</code>)</td><td>3 functions / 7 line hits: <code>__init__</code> L305, <code>_reset_per_run_state</code> L1553, <code>_run_agent_loop</code> L1405–1417 + L1532</td><td>3/3 verified against source — <b>exactly the paper's Appendix E answer key</b> (modulo snapshot drift)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The register view's real value: it converts a behavior question into an identifier you didn't know to grep for. The init and per-run reset sites are precisely what keyword search misses — nothing about "task_complete three times" suggests them, but the register's write-sites force them into scope.</p>

<p><b>What broke first-hand is as instructive as what worked.</b> Three failure modes from the probe: (1) The completion gate is ~15 lines <i>inside</i> a 310-line <code>_run_agent_loop</code> — function-granularity locators are too coarse, which validates the paper's contiguous-region mechanism as load-bearing, not a nicety. (2) Keyword-based stage assignment misfiled <code>_run_agent_loop</code> under "Prompt Assembly" because its parameter is named <code>original_instruction</code> — Phase II genuinely needs LLM judgment, yet the paper never ablates structuring quality (e.g., vs. cheap keyword/embedding assignment or an ablated no-review loop), so the handbook's accuracy ceiling is unmeasured. (3) Registers are shallow heuristics: <code>self._*</code> misses module-level globals, config dicts, and state passed through parameters — several of Terminus-2's real couplings travel through parameter passing, invisible to the register view.</p>

<p><b>The evaluation earns cautious trust, not full trust.</b> Headline numbers: handbook-assisted planning beats direct exploration by +10.0pp (Codex) and +18.9pp (Terminus-2) in judge-scored win rate, while using <i>fewer</i> planner tokens (−12.7% / −8.6%), and a weaker planner (DeepSeek-V4-Pro) with the handbook approaches reference plans from Opus 4.8 / GPT-5.5 (all 24 Recall/Precision/F1 comparisons improve, F1 gains +5.0 to +18.8). The caveats, earned by reading the appendix: the judges are three unreleased LLMs and <b>one of them is the planner itself</b>; the δ=3 win threshold on a 100-scale derived from 0.5-step scores is noise-level; the "reference plans" used for localization metrics are themselves unverified LLM outputs — the Codex F1 gain is +15.2 measured against Opus references but only +5.0 against GPT-5.5 references, and disagreement that large between the two "ground truths" tells you the truth is soft; the baseline arm is naked repo exploration, not a repo-map / Agentless-style localization baseline; and 30 requests per harness leaves ~10 per request-type cell. Since the planner and judge models are all unreleased, <b>none of the headline numbers are externally reproducible</b> — Appendix E's single walkthrough is the only executable evidence shown, which is exactly what the probe above reproduces.</p>

<p><b>What is actually new.</b> Coarse-to-fine localization is not new (Agentless and repo maps do versions of it). The contributions are: a <i>persistent</i> behavior-centric artifact rather than per-query retrieval; the cross-stage state-register view (empirically the piece that catches mirrored and cold-path sites); and the diff-triggered resync invariant that keeps the artifact aligned with the code. For the heuristic-learning thread — systems where a coding agent maintains an executable policy across iterations — this is the missing maintenance layer: a resynced handbook is a plausible shared behavioral memory between update rounds, and its "freeze, never guess" discipline is the right integrity rule for any agent-maintained index.</p>
<h1>Theme 3: A Game Engine, Fully Scriptable</h1>

<p>Photorealistic simulation has always forced an ugly trade: accept a hand-crafted API of a few hundred functions (AirSim: 92; CARLA: 465), or maintain a monolithic engine fork. SPEAR's answer is to stop wrapping the engine and instead hook Unreal's runtime reflection system — the same machinery that powers Blueprints — so that anything Blueprint-reachable becomes Python-reachable. The claim is 14,485 functions exposed with a modest 27 kLOC footprint, and it survives a code trace.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="200"/><col width="230"/><col width="230"/><col width="90"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Paper</th><th background-color="light-gray">Key Contribution</th><th background-color="light-gray">Why It Matters</th><th background-color="light-gray">Links</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><b>Self in Space (SIS-Bench)</b> (2026)</td><td>Benchmark for self-awareness and spatial cognition in UAV embodied intelligence — the agent's model of <i>itself</i>, not just the scene.</td><td>Embodied benchmarks are mostly environment-centric; self-representation is the unmeasured half.</td><td><a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.12477">HF</a> / <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.12477">PDF</a></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>SPEAR: A Simulator for Photorealistic Embodied AI Research</h2>
<p>Roberts et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.06701">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.06701">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/spear-sim/spear">code</a></p>

<p>This is the formal publication of the Intel Labs / Adobe SPEAR system (ECCV 2026), and it comes with the full repo. The trace confirms the central mechanism with unusual clarity: there is <b>no code generator and no per-function bindings anywhere in the repo</b>. One generic path does everything — Python attribute access resolves a UFunction by name string, a parameter buffer is allocated and filled from the function's reflected FProperty list (arguments travel as JSON strings, which is why Python dicts work as a universal representation), and the call goes through <code>uobject-&gt;ProcessEvent(ufunction, buf)</code> at <code>UnrealUtils.cpp:254</code> — literally the same dispatch path Blueprints use. Exposing new C++ functionality is adding a <code>UFUNCTION</code> annotation in any header, anywhere; no SPEAR-side registration is needed.</p>

<pre lang="cpp" caption="The entire trick: one generic reflection call path (UnrealUtils.cpp, trimmed)"><code>uint32 num_bytes = ufunction-&gt;ParmsSize;              // reflected param struct size
std::vector&lt;uint8_t&gt; args_vector(num_bytes, 0);
ufunction-&gt;InitializeStruct(args_vector.data());      // default-construct params
for (TFieldIterator&lt;FProperty&gt; itr(ufunction); itr; ++itr) { ... }   // walk params via reflection
for (auto&amp; [name, desc] : property_descs)
    setPropertyValueFromString(desc, args.at(name));  // UE JSON import: dicts -&gt; C++ values
uobject-&gt;ProcessEvent(ufunction, args_vector.data()); // THE call — same path as Blueprints</code></pre>

<p>The "14,485 UE functions + 53,537 UE properties" figure is a <i>runtime count over the loaded reflection registry</i> (their <code>examples/get_class_info/run.py</code> iterates every UClass and sums UFUNCTIONs), not a static binding set — it varies with engine version and loaded plugins. But the order-of-magnitude claim against the baselines is fair, and the hand-crafted surface is small: the paper says 193 entry points; a count at the current commit finds 208 (78% exist to expose the reflection system itself), the gap being version drift. Around that core: an rpclib msgpack-RPC server on its own thread inside the UE process, thread-safe work queues the game thread drains at frame boundaries, <code>begin_frame</code>/<code>end_frame</code> transactions with deterministic in-frame ordering, async variants of every entry point auto-generated by template metaprogramming, and a SpFunction + boost-shared-memory fast path so rendered frames land directly in a user-allocated NumPy array with zero copies.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="130"/><col width="130"/><col width="110"/><col width="110"/><col width="110"/><col width="110"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Simulator</th><th background-color="light-gray">Hand-crafted fns / vars</th><th background-color="light-gray">UE fns exposed</th><th background-color="light-gray">UE vars exposed</th><th background-color="light-gray">Lines of code</th><th background-color="light-gray">1080p→Python</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>AirSim</td><td>92 / 189</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>144,536</td><td>2.6 fps</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CARLA</td><td>465 / 508</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>150,502</td><td>32.7 fps</td></tr>
    <tr><td>UnrealCV+</td><td>56 / 0</td><td>747</td><td>8,721</td><td>11,301</td><td>3.5 fps</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>SPEAR</b></td><td><b>193 / 67</b></td><td><b>14,485</b></td><td><b>53,537</b></td><td><b>27,193</b></td><td><b>37.1–73.4 fps</b></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The performance claim holds up structurally: async communication and shared memory each buy measurable speed, and the camera sensor's configurable buffering (single/double/triple) is the paper's "rendering latency" knob — at two frames of latency SPEAR delivers 1920×1080 beauty renders into NumPy at 73.4 fps, 9–21× faster than UnrealCV+ measured like-for-like in the same project, 12× faster than AirSim, and 10% faster than CARLA at matched latency. The camera also emits Hypersim-grade ground truth (depth, normals, semantic/instance IDs, a non-diffuse intrinsic decomposition, material IDs, PBR shading parameters) that no other UE simulator provides.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:spear:agents]]</p>

<p><b>What this buys — and what it doesn't.</b> Anything Blueprint-reachable is Python-reachable with identical semantics: spawning actors, driving the procedural content generation system, Movie Render Queue, the path tracer, Enhanced Input, editor scripting, console variables. What it does not buy: type safety, docstrings, or discoverability (you fish for names via <code>find_functions_by_name</code>); non-reflectable C++ APIs still need the hand-crafted entry points; and the generic path stringifies arguments per call — fine for poses and actions, wrong for pixels, which is exactly why the SpFunction + shared-memory path exists. For a robotics data engine the honest verdict is nuanced. SPEAR is the most convincing "game engine as a <i>programmable</i> data engine" artifact to date, and 56–73 fps photorealistic rendering with rich GT is 10×-class better than any UE alternative. But it is not a ManiSkill3/Isaac competitor for physics-first manipulation training: UE Chaos is not GPU-batched, there is one instance per process, no gym wrapper or ROS bridge exists, and installation means an Epic account, UE 5.5 (or the ue-58 branch), and a full C++ plugin build — no Docker, no wheels. The compelling play is hybrid: MuJoCo/Isaac/ManiSkill dynamics with SPEAR as the photorealistic observation renderer — and the repo's own MuJoCo co-simulation example (UE state slaved to MuJoCo stepping with user substeps) is precisely that proof of concept. Also notable for this run's meta-theme: the repo ships an MCP server (<code>tools/run_mcp_server.py</code>) so a coding agent can edit scenes in natural language — the engine is explicitly being positioned as agent-operable infrastructure.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p><b>1. Interfaces are being redesigned for agent operation, and the honest ones share a pattern.</b> GigaWorld-Policy-0.5's recipe was produced by an agent loop (AutoResearch); the Harness Handbook is exposed to planners as a SKILL.md and keeps every locator revalidated against live source; SPEAR exposes the engine through its reflection registry and ships an MCP server. In all three, <b>deterministic ground truth carries the structure and the model supplies only the semantics</b>: static analysis + LLM stage assignment; reflection registry + name-string dispatch; bounded pilot runs + keep/discard metrics. And all three enforce some version of "log or freeze, never guess" — unresolved calls, unverifiable locators, failed pilots. As agents become the primary operators of these systems, this division of labor looks like the right integrity rule, and it is worth stealing for any agent-maintained artifact (including heuristic-learning systems that maintain executable policies).</p>

<p><b>2. Training–inference asymmetry is becoming a first-class design axis.</b> GigaWorld-Policy-0.5's mask makes the future stream exactly optional; last run's FlowWAM routed action through optical flow for the same reason; FastWAM's ablation (video co-training removal → 10% SR) shows the training-time objective is where the value lives. The field is converging on "imagine at training, act at test" — the interesting frontier is now what the training-time imagination should be conditioned on (this paper bets: the actions themselves).</p>

<p><b>3. Errata and honesty log for this run.</b> GigaWorld-Policy-0.5: Figure 6 legend appears swapped; repo config (action_dim=32) disagrees with the shipped checkpoint (16 channels); arXiv v1 bibliography is broken; the 85 ms C++ number has no baseline counterparts and the runtime is unshipped. Harness Handbook: no code, handbooks, requests, or traces released; judges include the planner itself; headline numbers are not externally reproducible. SPEAR: the 193-entry-point claim counts 208 at HEAD (benign drift), and the 14,485 figure is a runtime registry count, not a binding set. None of these overturn the papers' core claims, but all of them were invisible from the abstracts.</p>

